    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1959-09-29T19:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1959-09-29T19:10:00-05:00" n="75"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d75">
                <head>75. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Turkey</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d75fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 396.1–WA/9–2959. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_EHF1"
                            >Eilts</persName>; cleared by <persName>Jones</persName> and
                            <persName>Wright</persName>; cleared in draft by <persName
                            corresp="#p_HCAJ1">Herter</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_RGF1"
                            >Reinhardt</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JOT1">Owen
                        Jones</persName>, Moffet, and <persName corresp="#p_BFP1"
                            >Bartlett</persName>; and approved by <persName corresp="#p_MRD2"
                            >Murphy</persName>. Sent also to Karachi, London, and Tehran and
                        repeated to Baghdad, Kabul, and New Delhi.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1959-09-29T20:10:00-04:00">September 29, 1959, 8:10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1001. <gloss target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss>. Following are US objectives at
                    forthcoming <gloss target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss> Council session:<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d75fn1">October 6–7 in Washington.</note>
                    <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>To infuse, as necessary, an appreciation of continuing need for <gloss
                                target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss> and benefits regional states derive
                            from it.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>To persuade <gloss target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss>
                            members—particularly Iran—of our continuing strong support of <gloss
                                target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss> and its objectives.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>To reassure regional states <persName>Eisenhower</persName>–<persName
                                corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> exchange of visits<note
                                n="2" xml:id="d75fn2">
                                <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> visited the United
                                States September 15–27; <persName>Eisenhower</persName> did not
                                visit the Soviet Union.</note> does not alter US policy re <gloss
                                target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss>.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>To impress upon regional states that US military and economic aid
                            programs have been generous, are soundly based and materially enhance
                            their defense capabilities and their healthy economic
                            development.</item>
                        <pb facs="0273" n="239" xml:id="pg_239"/>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>As corollary, to impress on regional states that limited
                            appropriations make it impossible increase <gloss target="#t_MAP1"
                                >MAP</gloss> programs and that US and its partners in <gloss
                                target="#t_MSP1">MSP</gloss> will have to produce more for less
                            money in immediate period ahead.</item>
                        <label>6.</label>
                        <item>To exchange views freely and frankly on current <gloss target="#t_ME1"
                                >ME</gloss> problems, yet avoid any commitment to a common
                            policy.</item>
                        <label>7.</label>
                        <item>To impress upon Pakistan and Iran in particular that we are not
                            prepared to write off Afghanistan and Iraq as Soviet satellites and to
                            urge them, as appropriate, to take constructive action to improve their
                            relations with these states and with other free world neighbors.</item>
                        <label>8.</label>
                        <item>To dissuade discreetly regional states from undertaking <gloss
                                target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss> activities inconsistent with US
                            global and area-wide interests and to keep <gloss target="#t_CENTO1"
                                >CENTO</gloss> militarily and publicly out of existing intra-area
                            disputes.</item>
                        <label>9.</label>
                        <item>Since Iran is a key in <gloss target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss>
                            situation, particular attention should be focused on stiffening Iranian
                            morale through all reasonable means.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Be guided by foregoing in any discussion of specific issues likely arise at
                        <gloss target="#t_CENTO1">CENTO</gloss> session.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HCAJ1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Herter</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
